<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1864-12-23T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1864-12-23T00:00:00-05:00" n="336" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d336">
                        <head><persName type="from">Mr. Seward</persName> to <persName type="to">Mr.
                                Pennington</persName></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State;</hi>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Washington,</hi></placeName>
                                <date calendar="gregorian" when="1864-12-23"><hi rend="italic">December</hi> 23, 1864.</date></dateline></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir:</hi> I have received your despatch of the 2d
                            instant, No. 1, announcing to this department the sudden death of the
                            Hon. William L. Dayton, minister resident of the United States at
                            Paris.</p>
                        <p>You are instructed to commit the archives of the legation to J. Bigelow,
                            esq., late the United States consul at Paris, who has been appointed
                            charge d’affaires <hi rend="italic">ad interim.</hi></p>
                        <p>I am, sir, your obedient servant,</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>WILLIAM H. SEWARD.</signed></closer>
                        <postscript>
                            <p>W. S. <hi rend="smallcaps">Pennington,</hi> Esq., <hi rend="italic">&amp;c., &amp;c., &amp;c</hi>.</p>
                        </postscript>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>